{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17412768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17412768"},"attributes":{"position":4,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T07:38:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T07:38:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1261"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493237"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:01:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:01:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1261"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261074"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:38:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:40:20+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":19,"questionsAnswered":7,"marksTotal":19,"marksAttainable":7,"marksAttempted":7,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T07:39:59+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.14,"questionsCorrect":1,"marksCorrect":1},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"1261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1261"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.73,0.03,0.19,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1261"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96531"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1261","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1261"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1261"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79173"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"4847"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2272"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2526"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32464"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32747"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33089"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42265"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96531","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96531"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman with known multiple myeloma presents to the Emergency Department complaining of worsening confusion and constipation for the last week. She has also had poor oral intake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her mucous membranes are dry and her tongue is coated. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 110/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Her capillary refill is 3 seconds. She is confused and not oriented to time or place, but she can tell you her full name. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer blood tests are significant for a calcium level of 3.0 mmol/L (2.2-2.8). An ECG shows a shortened QT interval.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IV normal saline","IV methylprednisolone","IV bisphosphonate","IV frusemide","Haemodialysis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHypercalcaemia is the most common metabolic complication of multiple myeloma due to excessive osteolysis. The symptoms of multiple myeloma can be remembered by the acronym - CRAB (calcium - high, renal impairment, anaemia and bony lesions). The symptoms of high calcium can be remembered by the saying bones (pain), groans (nausea, vomiting, constipation), thrones (frequent urination), stones (renal colic) and psychic moans (depression, irritability). As described in this case the patient is suffering from confusion, constipation and dehydration, which may be a result of excessive urination and a deterioration in renal function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV normal saline\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step as volume expansion is critical to improve renal blood flow and enhance calcium excretion. This patient shows clear signs of dehydration with dry mucous membranes, prolonged capillary refill, and confusion. Importantly, adequate hydration must be established before administering bisphosphonates to prevent calcium-phosphate crystal deposition in the kidneys, which can cause acute kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV bisphosphonate\u003C/strong\u003E therapy is an important component of treatment but should only be initiated after adequate volume expansion has been achieved. These medications work by inhibiting osteoclast activity but take 24-48 hours to show effect. Administering bisphosphonates without prior fluid resuscitation can lead to acute kidney injury due to calcium-phosphate crystal deposition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV methylprednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E may be used in cases of vitamin D-mediated hypercalcaemia or granulomatous conditions, but is not indicated as first-line therapy for myeloma-related hypercalcaemia. It would not address the urgent need for volume repletion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV frusemide\u003C/strong\u003E was historically used in hypercalcaemia management but is now discouraged as first-line therapy as it can worsen the underlying volume depletion. It may be considered after adequate volume expansion has been achieved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemodialysis\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for severe cases with refractory hypercalcaemia or significant renal dysfunction. It would be excessive as an initial intervention in this case where more conservative measures should be tried first.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypercalcaemia requires IV fluid rehydration before bisphosphonate administration to prevent acute kidney injury","Multiple myeloma commonly presents with hypercalcaemia due to excessive osteolysis","ECG findings in hypercalcaemia include shortened QT interval and prolonged PR interval"],"references":["Eslick, R and Talaulikar, D, 2013. Multiple Myeloma: from diagnosis to treatment. RACGP. Volume 42, No.10, October 2013 Pages 684-688. Access at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2013/october/multiple-myeloma/#:~:text=The%20classical%20complications%20are%20often,those%20with%20newly%20diagnosed%20myeloma..","Oyajobi BO. Multiple myeloma/hypercalcemia. Arthritis Res Ther. 2007;9 Suppl 1(Suppl 1):S4. doi:10.1186/ar2168","Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd. Hypercalcaemia (Internet). 2019. Access at: https://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.proxy.library.adelaide.edu.au/viewTopic?topicfile=hypercalcaemia\u0026guidelineName=Bone%20and%20Metabolism\u0026topicNavigation=navigateTopic#toc_d1e123.","Prescribing Guidelines for HYPER-Electrolyte Disturbances in Adults. Queensland Health. Available from: https://www.health.qld.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0027/1006587/electrolyte-prescribe-gline-adult.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79173"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1261"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79173","links":{